      <h2>Vented vs Unvented Hot Water Cylinders. Which Do You Need?</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">The right cylinder for your Liverpool home depends on your property type, water pressure and hot water demand. We advise at the free survey.</p>

      <div class="pf-who-grid" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Vented cylinder. Traditional Liverpool properties.</strong><p>A vented (or open-vented) cylinder is fed from a cold water storage tank in the loft. Common in Liverpool's older Victorian and Edwardian properties. Operates at low pressure and is simple to maintain. A good choice for properties where the existing loft tank system is working correctly and mains pressure hot water is not required.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Unvented cylinder. Mains pressure hot water.</strong><p>An unvented cylinder is fed directly from the mains supply, delivering hot water at mains pressure throughout the property. Much better shower performance. No cold water tank needed in the loft. Ideal for larger Liverpool properties with multiple bathrooms. Must be installed by a G3 qualified engineer under Building Regulations Part G. All our engineers are G3 qualified.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Direct cylinder. Heated by immersion heater only.</strong><p>A direct cylinder uses an electric immersion heater as its primary or sole heat source. Common in all-electric properties or as a backup heating method. Useful during boiler repairs or as a solar thermal storage cylinder. We fit immersion heaters from £150 and supply direct cylinders from £500.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Indirect cylinder. Heated by your boiler.</strong><p>An indirect cylinder is heated by the central heating boiler via a heat exchanger coil inside the cylinder. The most common type in Liverpool homes with system or regular boilers. Usually also has an immersion heater as a backup. We supply and fit indirect cylinders in both vented and unvented configurations.</p></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SIGNS YOU NEED A NEW CYLINDER -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Signs Your Liverpool Hot Water Cylinder Needs Replacing</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Most Liverpool homes with system or regular boilers rely on a hot water cylinder. These are the signs that replacement is due.</p>

      <div class="pf-signs" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Running out of hot water frequently</strong><p>If your household regularly exhausts the hot water before everyone has showered, the cylinder is undersized for your current demand. A larger cylinder or an unvented system delivers more hot water to more outlets simultaneously.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Cylinder is leaking</strong><p>A leaking cylinder must be replaced. Cylinders cannot be repaired once the tank itself has failed. A small drip from a valve or fitting can sometimes be resolved without replacing the cylinder. We diagnose which is the case on the visit.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Hot water takes a very long time to reheat</strong><p>A cylinder that takes more than 30 to 45 minutes to reheat after being used usually has a failing immersion heater element, a corroded heat exchanger coil or a faulty thermostat. We diagnose the cause before recommending replacement.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Cylinder is over 20 years old</strong><p>Most hot water cylinders have a working life of 15 to 25 years. An older cylinder is likely losing efficiency, may have internal corrosion and is at greater risk of failure. Proactive replacement avoids an emergency and the water damage that can follow a sudden cylinder failure.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Poor hot water pressure throughout the property</strong><p>If hot water pressure is poor in your Liverpool home despite good cold water pressure, the issue is usually the cylinder type. Moving from a vented system to an unvented cylinder eliminates this problem and delivers mains-pressure hot water to every outlet in the house.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Noisy cylinder or pipework</strong><p>Banging or kettling from the cylinder or its pipework indicates limescale build-up on the immersion heater element or heat exchanger, or air in the system. Often resolved with an element replacement before full cylinder replacement is needed.</p></div></div>
      </div>

